{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/corticosteroids-oral/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"f776021e-e349-55a4-b655-4801dd7df8e5","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 9aaa5f17-f4f2-43c8-9fb8-a781f914afce --><h2>What are corticosteroids?</h2><!-- end field 9aaa5f17-f4f2-43c8-9fb8-a781f914afce -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 41927591-f034-48ee-86c2-fd5888ad000e --><!-- begin field 95172adf-589b-4a03-ab6b-b086f4ae2181 --><ul><li>Corticosteroids are synthetic analogues of hormones that are produced by the adrenal cortex. </li><li>Synthetic corticosteroids can have glucocorticoid and mineralocorticoid <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/corticosteroids-oral/background-information/properties-of-corticosteroids/\">properties</a>. <ul><li>Different corticosteroids have varying ratios of mineralocorticoid to glucocorticoid properties. The ratio determines the corticosteroid's efficacy and therapeutic use.</li></ul></li><li>Corticosteroids can be administered systemically (orally and parenterally) or locally (by inhalation, topically, intranasally, intraocularly, rectally, and by intra-articular injection).</li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/corticosteroids-oral/references/\">Brayfield, 2020</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/corticosteroids-oral/references/\">Ritter, 2020</a>]</p><!-- end field 95172adf-589b-4a03-ab6b-b086f4ae2181 --><!-- end item 41927591-f034-48ee-86c2-fd5888ad000e -->","topic":{"id":"2ddb5306-0521-5967-b3ad-e150e92dd71e","topicId":"72c594bc-4c91-4d24-acdb-dda9812ea656","topicName":"Corticosteroids - oral","slug":"corticosteroids-oral","lastRevised":"Last revised in June 2020","chapters":[{"id":"de758570-b276-5b9a-b679-243ca11b5b0b","fullItemName":"Summary","slug